[Student "S"]
{Of course you open 1\S. Partner responds 2\C.  

With 17 points and a 6-card suit you jump to 3\S. Partner bids the game.

North plays 4\S. East leads the \HQ.

<b>North plays 4\S. East leads the \HQ.</b>

Losers: \S 1 : \H 1 : \D 2 : \C 0 : Total = 4

You have plenty of \C winners in dummy but you must be careful because there are no outside entries. You win your \HA and play \SA and \SK, both defenders following suit. The \SQ is still out. To make sure you get to enjoy those \C winners you should continue with another \S, forcing out the \SQ. The defense will now take a \H if they are smart, but the rest of the tricks are yours because you can run the \C suit without anyone trumping in.

Think through what would have happened if you had not forced out the \SQ.

West would have used his master \SQ to ruff the second \C, before you had taken any discards. You would still have to lose a \H and two \Ds.}
[Play "W"]HQ

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:K864.QJ3.AK2.A95 952.A72.74.JT643 AJ3.T864.Q965.87 QT7.K95.JT83.KQ2"]
